{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The content passed to the summary-generation step includes data retrieved from all three sources.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Pairwise: Unit vs Integration -> Integration wins because the failure boundary is module handoff (three collectors -> aggregation payload), not a single function. Integration vs System -> Integration wins because this behavior can be validated with in-process stubs for the three source clients; no real OS/network/subprocess is required. Integration brake: (a) no real infra required, (b) correctness is payload completeness not model judgment, (c) no multi-agent chain, (d) no LLM-governed stage handoff. Rejection gate: rejected System/Agentic since behavior text is about \"content passed\" including all three sources, not external transport behavior or model output quality.","test_description":"Wire real aggregator/orchestrator modules with stubbed source adapters returning distinct sentinel records from metrics, issue tracker, and deploy log. Execute one run and assert the exact payload sent to summary-generation contains all three source sections and expected keys/values.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When one data source is unavailable, the report is produced with a `data unavailable` note for that section rather than aborting.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Pairwise: Unit vs Integration -> Integration wins because failure appears at orchestration boundary (error from one source must propagate into partial-report state). Integration vs System -> Integration wins since unavailability can be reproduced with an in-process failing adapter and checked in assembled report output. Integration brake: (a) no mandatory real OS/network, (b) assertion is fallback behavior not model quality, (c) no multi-agent sequence, (d) no LLM decision handoff required. Rejection gate: rejected System because behavior text specifies graceful degradation logic (\"rather than aborting\"), which is catchable via module wiring without real infrastructure.","test_description":"Run report pipeline with two source adapters returning normal data and one adapter raising timeout/unavailable error. Assert run completes, report includes `data unavailable` marker only for failed section, and process does not terminate early.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.55,"System":0.15,"Agentic":0.1,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The narrative summary accurately represents the key values present in the input data.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Pairwise: Unit vs Integration -> Integration wins (summary component consumes structured input from upstream). Integration vs System -> Integration would normally win (no inherent OS need). Integration vs Agentic -> Agentic wins because correctness depends on actual summary quality/judgment (\"accurately represents\"), which deterministic mocks can hide. Rejection gate: rejected Workflow because behavior text covers one summary-generation decision, not multiple agentic steps in sequence.","test_description":"Feed representative weekly input datasets with known key values into the real summary-generation model/service. Evaluate output for factual inclusion/correctness of key metrics/issues/deploy outcomes using rubric-based assertions across repeated runs to detect model-output failure modes.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.7,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"A complete report — from data collection through email delivery — reaches the configured recipient's inbox correctly.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Pairwise: Unit vs Integration -> Integration wins (multi-module pipeline). Integration vs System -> System wins because failure boundary includes real HTTP/API connectivity and real email delivery/inbox reception. Rejection gate: rejected Agentic because behavior text is delivery outcome (\"reaches ... inbox correctly\"), not summary-quality judgment; a fixed summary fixture is sufficient for this assertion.","test_description":"Execute the scheduled script in a production-like environment against real internal endpoints (or staging equivalents) and real email infrastructure, then verify the message is delivered to configured recipient inbox with expected headers/body sections and no pipeline crash.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.09,"System":0.75,"Agentic":0.1,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the email delivery service is unreachable, the generated report is saved to a local file and delivery is retried on the next scheduled run.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Pairwise: Unit vs Integration -> Integration wins (handoff among generation, persistence, and retry state). Integration vs System -> System wins because behavior requires real filesystem persistence plus scheduler/run-boundary behavior and unreachable delivery endpoint semantics. Rejection gate: rejected Workflow because this is retry/persistence across runs, not multiple LLM decisions; rejected Agentic because correctness is transport fallback/retry, not model output quality.","test_description":"Induce real email endpoint unreachability (network block or service stop), run scheduler once, assert report file exists on disk with expected content, then restore email service and run next scheduled execution; assert queued report is retried and successfully delivered.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.13,"System":0.75,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.05}}]}
